coredata.dc:description: AA 3104 aluminium alloy was deformed at a temperature of 510°C and at a strain rate of 5 s−1 to strains of 0.14, 0.53, 1.52, and 2.49 by plane strain compression. The effect of grain orientation on microstructures has been investigated using transmission electron microscopy (TEM). The results show that the grain orientation has a strong effect on the microstructures at low strains. The microstructures can be classified into three types according to the process of grain subdivision and the characteristics of dislocation boundaries. Every type of microstructure is concentrated in a positive district in orientation distribution figure. The microstructures in grains near the brass and S orientations correspond to the Type AI microstructure. The grains near the copper orientation appear as a Type AII microstructure. The Type B microstructure is found in the region near the rotated Goss orientation. The Type C microstructure is concentrated in the cube orientation. At large strains approximately equiaxed subgrains are observed.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para: AA 3104 aluminium alloy was deformed at a temperature of 510°C and at a strain rate of 5 s−1 to strains of 0.14, 0.53, 1.52, and 2.49 by plane strain compression. The effect of grain orientation on microstructures has been investigated using transmission electron microscopy (TEM). The results show that the grain orientation has a strong effect on the microstructures at low strains. The microstructures can be classified into three types according to the process of grain subdivision and the characteristics of dislocation boundaries. Every type of microstructure is concentrated in a positive district in orientation distribution figure. The microstructures in grains near the brass and S orientations correspond to the Type AI microstructure. The grains near the copper orientation appear as a Type AII microstructure. The Type B microstructure is found in the region near the rotated Goss orientation. The Type C microstructure is concentrated in the cube orientation. At large strains approximately equiaxed subgrains are observed.

ce:section.ce:para: The microstructural evolution during cold deformation of f.c.c. polycrystals with high stacking fault energies has been studied extensively [1–12]. In general the microstructure is subdivided into cell-blocks containing ordinary dislocation cells. The cell-block boundaries are geometrically necessary boundaries (GNBs) and the cell boundaries are incidental dislocation boundaries (IDBs) formed by mutual trapping of glide dislocations [1–6]. It has been observed that with increasing strain the misorientation angle across the two types of boundaries increases and that the spacing between the boundaries decreases.

The deformed microstructures depend strongly on the grain orientation. Such an orientation effect has been found in many studies of single crystals [7–10]. The effect of grain orientation on deformed microstructures in polycrystalline materials has also been observed [11–14]. Huang [12, 13] found that there is a strong correlation between the type of dislocation structure developed in a grain and the crystallographic orientation of the grain for f.c.c. polycrystalline materials deformed in tension. Moreover, the stereographic triangle representing all possible crystallographic orientations in axisymmetric tension is divided by into five regions based on the correlation between the preferred crystallographic boundary planes and the grain orientation [15]. The effect of grain orientation on microstructures of aluminium polycrystalline materials deformed in cold rolling has been reported in detail [14].

Some studies on the microstructural evolution during hot deformation of aluminium alloys have been carried out [16–21]. The microstructures have been discussed in detail for deformation at 305°C [19]. A major feature of the deformed microstructures is the occurrence of microbands (MB) within the grains. These MB boundaries are less complex than the dense dislocation walls (DDWs) and MBs observed after room temperature deformation of aluminium alloys [20]. A structure of parallel dislocation walls, lying in one direction, was observed in the early stage of deformation at 400°C in an Al–Mg alloy [21]. However, the effect of grain orientation on microstructures during hot deformation has not been reported.

In order to describe quantitatively the relationship between the parameters representing the microstructures and the process parameters, it is necessary to determine the misorientation across the dislocation boundaries besides the boundary spacing and the size of dislocation cells or subgrains. A quantitative analysis of the misorientation angles has, however, only recently been possible by the introduction of semi-automatic and automatic microscopic techniques for the determination of local crystallographic orientations on the micrometer and submicrometer scales [22–26]. Thus, there are a few reports which have measured the misorientation angles across dislocation boundaries formed during hot deformation [19, 20, 27].

In the present work the microstructures in different grains with different orientations in the samples deformed at a temperature of 510°C and a strain rate of 5 s−1 were observed by transmission electron microscope. The misorientation angles across dislocation boundaries and the spacing of dislocation boundaries as well as the cell and subgrain size were measured. The Euler space representing all crystallographic orientations in plane strain compression was divided into different regions to show the correlation between the type of microstructure and grain orientation.

The material used in the present investigation is AA 3104 aluminium alloy (Al–1.25Mg–1.01Mn–0.47Fe–0.21Ti–0.20Si–0.17Cu). From the cast ingot, specimens were industrially hot rolled on a reversible mill from a thickness of 385 to 12 mm and subjected to an intermediate heat treatment. Specimens were machined from the strip and deformed at a temperature of 510°C and at a strain rate of 5 s−1 to strains of 0.14, 0.53, 1.52, and 2.49 by plane strain compression. The specimens were rapidly quenched with water sprays immediately after testing to limit recovery and recrystallization and allow the observation and measurement of the deformed microstructures.

The deformation microstructures were observed in a JEOL 2000FX electron microscope operating at 200 kV. The thin foils for TEM observation were prepared from the longitudinal plane sections of the deformed samples. With the aid of a TEM double-tilt holder, a semi-automatic method [26] was used to determine the orientation of individual crystallites, and then the misorientation angles across dislocation boundaries were calculated based on the orientation information. The boundary distance and the sizes of dislocation cells or subgrains were measured.

The microstructures in different grains with different orientations in the samples deformed at a temperature of 510°C and a strain rate of 5 s−1 were observed by TEM. It is generally found that the microstructures undergo a continuous evolution from a structure of extended dislocation boundaries to a subgrain structure. In the early stage of deformation the microstructural characteristics of individual grains are strongly affected by grain orientation. At large strains the well-defined subgrains are formed.

Figure 1 shows the microstructures of a grain with (−0.60 0.55 −0.56) [−0.78 −0.31 0.53] orientation, which was taken under a diffraction condition with the [011] zone axis nearly parallel to the incident electron beam. In Fig. 1(a) it is seen that the grain is separated by some long and straight dislocation boundaries into some larger regions marked A, B, C, D, E, F. The boundaries have high misorientation angles (see Table 1 ). The boundary spacing is very wide. For convenience we refer here, and in the following, to this type of dislocation boundary as the boundary I. In this grain boundary Is are lying at a positive angle of 37° to the rolling direction (Positive angles are anticlockwise to RD), spaced at average 21 μm. Between the boundary Is the microstructures are different from one region to the other. In the region (marked A) near the grain boundary the dislocation boundaries are well developed [Fig. 1(b)]. In the region (marked B) the dislocation boundaries just start to form along the direction parallel to boundary Is [Fig. 1(c)]. In the region (marked F) a set of dislocation boundaries is formed along the direction of −51° to RD [Fig. 1(d)]. The average boundary spacing between these dislocation boundaries is 2.0 μm, which is much less than that of boundary Is. The boundaries are referred to hereafter as Boundary IIs. By the trace analysis [28], the boundary IIs are inclined 9° to the trace of (
1 ̄ 11) slip plane or −9° to the trace of (111) slip plane (positive angles are anticlockwise to the trace of a {111} slip plane). Careful observation reveals that the boundary IIs are not straight, but exhibit curvature in small segments of the boundaries, that is, the boundary plane varies with its location along the boundary. Between these boundary IIs a few dislocation boundaries can be observed, which are terminated at the boundary IIs, appearing as short lines perpendicular to the boundary IIs. In fact, the formation of these boundaries is also regarded as a kind of grain subdivisions and they are referred to as the boundary IIIs. The misorientation angles across the boundary IIIs are lower than those across the boundary IIs (see Table 1).
Figure 2 shows the microstructures of a grain with (−0.51 0.86 0.03) [−0.81 −0.47 −0.34] orientation. A lot of dislocations can be observed, but no dislocation boundaries are formed.
Figure 3 shows the microstructures of a grain with (0.93 −0.34 0.03) [0.30 0.77 −0.56] orientation. The dislocation boundaries just start to form.

Figure 4 shows the formation of boundaries in a grain with (0.08 0.62 −0.79) [−0.91 −0.28 −0.31] orientation, where the area is about 44×44 μm2. In this case, the boundary Is are not observed, but a set of boundaries is well developed within the whole area. The boundaries are lying at an angle of 26° to RD, which is −3° to the trace of the nearest (11 1 ̄ ) plane.

Figure 5 shows the microstructures of a grain with (−0.63 0.76 −0.16) [−0.75 −0.65 −0.11] orientation. It is seen that two sets of boundaries are developed symmetrically with an angle of −38° and 31° to RD. The misorientations along these two directions are analysed, and the distribution of misorientations and their average values are found to be almost identical. The trace analysis shows that the boundaries are not parallel to the trace of {111} plane. The angles between the traces of the boundaries and the traces of the nearest (1 1 ̄ 1) and (11 1 ̄ ) planes are −28° and −45°, respectively.

Figure 6 shows the microstructures of a grain with (−0.25 0.95 −0.18) [−0.97 −0.25 0.01] orientation, which is 18° from the (010) [−100] cube orientation. A lot of dislocations can be observed, but the distribution of dislocations seems to be different from that shown in Fig. 3.

In addition, the microstructures of other grains with different orientations have been observed. Table 1 shows the grain orientation, the characteristics of microstructures, the macroscopic orientation of boundaries to RD, the angle between the trace of boundary IIs and the nearest {111} trace, average misorientation angle of boundaries, and average width of boundary IIs.

At a strain of 0.53, the microstructures with the elongated cells formed at a strain of 0.14 are changed into the subgrain microstructures, while the grains with a lot of dislocations or with a set of boundary IIs at a strain of 0.14 are now separated by dislocation boundaries into elongated cells or square cells. Grain orientation still has a strong effect on microstructures. Figures 7–10
show the typical microstructures formed at a strain of 0.53.

Figure 7 shows the microstructures of a grain with (−0.74 0.67 −0.04) [−0.56 −0.58 0.58] orientation. A set of boundaries IIs is well developed at 26° to RD. The regions between the boundary IIs are separated by a few boundary IIIs into the elongated cells. It is clear that the microstructures are slowly developed in this grain since the microstructures closely resemble those in some grains at a strain of 0.14.

Figure 8 shows the microstructures of a grain with (0.15 0.75 −0.64) [−0.95 0.30 0.12] orientation. The microstructures contain elongated cells, but the ratio of length to width of cells is less than that in Fig. 7.

Figure 9 shows the microstructures of a grain with (−0.90 0.35 −0.23) [−0.42 −0.69 0.58] orientation. Approximately equiaxed subgrains are seen. However, there are observable long-range boundaries, that is, boundaries that are still nearly straight over a longer distance although they meander from linearity across cells. Thus, subgrain boundaries are likely the evolution of the linear boundaries observed at a strain of 0.14. The rectangular cells trend to form equiaxed subgrains during hot deformation.

Figure 10 shows the microstructures of a grain with (0.99 0.05 0.09) [−0.07 0.98 0.19] orientation. The characteristics of microstructure are somewhat different from those observed above. The microstructures are composed of large cells and cell blocks with many small cells, which is similar to that observed in the cube single crystal deformed at room temperature [29]. The large cells and small cells trend to be approximately equiaxed. The boundaries between large cells and cell blocks have higher misorientation angles, while the misorientation angle across boundaries in the cell blocks is smaller.

In addition, the microstructures of the other grains with different orientations have been observed. Table 2 shows the grain orientation, the characteristics of microstructures, the macroscopic orientation of boundaries to RD, the angle between the trace of boundaries and the nearest {111} trace, the average misorientation angle of boundaries, and the average width and length of cells or subgrains and the ratio of length to width.

At these strains the microstructures consist of equiaxed subgrains. Tables 3 and 4
show the misorientation angle of subgrain boundaries and the size of subgrains in different grains at strains of 1.52 and 2.49. Figure 11 shows the typical microstructures in a grain with (0.08 0.88 −0.47) [−0.98 0.17 0.13] orientation. The microstructures are consistent with previous results on Al–Mg alloys [19,20].

Based on the preceding results, it is found that grain orientation has a strong effect on microstructures at low strains. In general, microstructures can be classified into three types according to the grain subdivision and the characteristics of dislocation boundaries. Their characteristics is summarized as follows:
Type A: The grains are separated by a set of dislocation boundaries (boundary II) with a spacing of a few micrometers, and then the regions between boundary IIs are separated by dislocation boundaries (boundary III) into cells (Figs 1–4, 7–9). According to the crystallographic preference of boundary II, the structures (Type A) can be classified into two types, one (Type AI) with boundary IIs which are on {111} planes, that is, the trace of boundary IIs is <5° from the nearest slip plane (Figs 3 and 4), the other (Type AII) with boundary IIs which are not on {111} planes, that is, the trace of boundary IIs is >5° from the nearest slip plane (Figs 1, 7 and 8). For the Type A microstructure, some grains also undergo a macroscopic subdivision on the grain size scale before the formation of boundary IIs (Fig. 1).
Type B: The grains are directly separated by two sets of dislocation boundaries into cells. There are high angles between the traces of boundaries and the nearest {111} trace (Fig. 5).
Type C: The microstructures are composed of large cells and cell blocks with many small cells. The boundaries between cell blocks and large cells have higher misorientation angles than those in cell blocks (Fig. 10). Compared with Type A, the cell block boundaries have very high misorientation angles.
Figure 12 shows the relationship between the type of microstructure and grain orientation at strains of 0.14 and 0.53 in orientation distribution figure. In this figure the microstructural differences are introduced by using different symbols for the three types of microstructures and the subgrain structure formed at a strain of 0.53. At the same time the typical orientations such as the cube, Goss, rotated cube, rotated Goss, brass, copper and S {123}〈634〉 orientations are marked in Fig. 12. This figure indicates that the type of microstructure depends on the grain orientation. The microstructures in grains near the brass, S and copper orientations correspond to the Type A microstructure. The Type B microstructure has orientations around the rotated Goss orientation. The Type C microstructure is concentrated in the cube orientation.

Figure 12 shows that most of the observed grains have the Type A microstructure. Although the microstructural evolution is similar for the copper, brass and S orientations, the degree of development is different at the same strains. The misorientation angle across boundaries and the boundary spacing also vary with grain orientation. At a strain of 0.14, the boundaries are not formed in a grain with (0.08 0.62 −0.79) [−0.91 −0.28 −0.31] orientations (Fig. 2). The boundaries have just started to form, having low misorientation angles in a grain with (0.93 −0.34 0.03) [0.30 0.77 −0.56] orientation (Fig. 3). A set of boundary IIs is well developed and have higher misorientation angles, but the boundary IIIs are hardly formed in the regions between the boundary IIs in a grain with the (0.08 0.62 −0.79) [−0.91 −0.28 −0.31] orientations (Fig. 4). A set of boundary IIs is well developed, and the regions between the boundary IIs are separated by the boundary IIIs into cells in a grain with (0.84 −0.20 −0.50) [−0.37 0.45 −0.81] orientation. At a strain of 0.53, grain orientation still affects the development of microstructures. A set of boundary IIs is well developed, but there are a few boundary IIIs which separates the region between boundary IIs into elongated cells in a grain with (−0.74 0.67 −0.04) [−0.56 −0.58 0.58] orientation (Fig. 7). The microstructures reveal approximately square cells in a grain with (0.15 0.75 −0.64) [−0.95 0.30 0.12] orientation (Fig. 8). Approximately equiaxed subgrains are found in a grain with (−0.90 0.35 −0.23) [−0.42 −0.69 0.58] orientation (Fig. 9). This suggests that the development of microstructure is inhomogeneous due to the difference of grain orientation.

Tables 1 and 2 list the macroscopic orientation of the boundary IIs relative to RD. Although the average angle between the boundary IIs and RD decreases with increasing strain, the macroscopic orientations at strains of 0.14 and 0.53 only have a little difference. Figure 13 shows the distribution of angles of the total number of boundary IIs to RD. For the different type of microstructure, most of the boundary IIs have a common macroscopic orientation with an angle between 25 and 55° to RD, although the crystallographic orientation of boundary IIs varies with grain orientation. Their mean orientation is about 36° to RD, which is similar to the orientation of MBs observed in samples deformed at 305°C [19].

In order to describe quantitatively the characteristics of microstructures, >1500 dislocation boundaries of different types have been analysed at strains of 0.14–2.49. The average angles across dislocation boundaries of different types in different grains are presented in Tables 1–4. It is found that there are big differences among the misorientations of the different types of boundaries for the different types of microstructures.

For the Type A microstructure, in the early stage of deformation, three categories of dislocation boundaries are mainly considered based on grain subdivision, namely:
1.
boundary Is, which separate the grain on the grain size scale;
2.
boundary IIs, which include a set of long boundaries with the boundary spacing similar to the size of subgrains formed at large strains;
3.
boundary IIIs, which are formed between boundary IIs and separate the regions between boundary IIs into cells.

Tables 1 and 2 show the average misorientation angles across boundary Is, boundary IIs, and boundary IIIs in different grains. The average misorientation angle decreases in the sequence of boundary Is, boundary IIs and boundary IIIs at a given strain and grain orientation. Although there are differences among the misorientations of the three types of boundaries, these boundaries should have a similar character since they are converted into subgrain boundaries at large strains.

Figure 14 shows the typical histograms of misorientation angle across all boundaries at different strains for the Type A microstructure. These data are also plotted in Fig. 15 . Comparing the distribution of misorientation angle at different strains, it is found that with increasing strain, the maximum frequency of misorientation angle decreases, correspondingly the orientation distribution widens and the maximum misorientation angle increases.

Figure 16 shows the histograms of misorientation angle across boundary IIs for the Type AI and AII microstructures and across subgrain boundaries at strains of 0.14 and 0.53. It is noted that the misorientation angle across boundary IIs for the Type AI microstructure is lower than for the Type AII microstructure at strains of 0.14 and 0.53, which is in agreement with those observed in aluminium alloy deformed in cold rolling [14]. However, their difference at high temperature is less than at room temperature. The subgrain boundary has the highest misorientation angle among the crystallographic boundary, non-crystallographic boundary and subgrain boundary at a strain of 0.53.

Figure 17 shows the variation in the average misorientation angle across all boundaries with strain for the Type A microstructure. The misorientation angle increases with increasing strain. When the strain reaches 1.5, the misorientation angle still increases with strain. It is clear that it does not reach a steady state value [19].

For the Type B microstructure, two sets of boundaries, which have almost identical average misorientation angles, are developed at a strain of 0.14. Figure 18 shows the histogram of misorientation angles across all boundaries. The average misorientation angle is close to that for the Type A microstructure. At large strains the microstructures with the rotated Goss orientation are not observed since the volume fraction of the rotated Goss component is quite small.

For the Type C microstructure, the dislocation boundaries are not formed at a strain of 0.14. At a strain of 0.53 the grain is separated by cell blocks into large cells. Figure 19 shows the histograms of misorientation angle across the boundaries in cell blocks and between cell blocks and large cells as well as all boundaries. The misorientation angle across the boundaries in cell blocks is obviously lower than that between cell blocks and large cells. Compared with the misorientation angles for the Type A and B microstructures, the Type C microstructure has a higher misorientation angle (Fig. 17). At strains of 1.52 and 2.49, the grain with the cube orientation is not found.

For the Type A microstructure, a set of boundary IIs is formed in most of the grains. The distances between the boundary IIs were measured along the direction perpendicular to the boundaries. Their results are listed in Table 1. It is found that the average distance between the boundary IIs varies with grain orientation. Figure 20(a) shows the typical distribution of boundary spacing as a histogram. Their average boundary spacing is 2.1 μm. For the Type B microstructure, the dislocation boundaries are formed along the two directions, which separate grains into elongated cells. In order to describe the shape of the cells, the length and width of elongated cells were measured. The distributions of the width (w) and length (l) of cells and the ratio of length to width (l/w) are shown in Fig. 20(b–d), where their average values are 2.30 μm, 4.78 μm and 2.16, respectively. Comparing the Type A microstructure with the Type B microstructure, it is found that although the Type A microstructure is different from the Type B microstructure, the boundary spacing for Type A microstructure is similar to the width of cells for Type B microstructure. However, the l/w value for the Type A microstructure is markedly larger than that for the Type B microstructure. For the Type C microstructure, no boundaries are formed at low strains.

For the Type A microstructure, the microstructures formed at low strains continue to develop with increasing strain. However, the difference in microstructures still exists. In some grains the microstructures are found to be elongated cells or approximately square cells. In other grains approximately equiaxed subgrains are found. The length and width of cells or subgrains were still measured to determine the variation in size and shape of the cells or subgrains with strain. Figure 21 shows the histograms of the width and length of elongated cells, approximately square cells and subgrains as well as the ratio of length to width. It is seen that as the microstructures change from elongated cells to approximately equiaxed subgrains, the length of cells and subgrains and the ratio of length to width decrease markedly, whereas the width of cells and subgrains changes a little.

For the Type C microstructure, the microstructures consist of small cells and large cells. The histograms of the width and length of small cells and large cells as well as the ratio of length to width are shown in Fig. 22 . The small cells and large cells are approximately equiaxed. The size of small cells in cell blocks for the Type C microstructure are similar to the subgrain size found in some grains with the Type A microstructure.

Figure 23 shows the histograms of the width and length of subgrains and the ratio of length to width at strains of 1.52 and 2.49. The ratio of length to width of subgrains tends to decrease with increasing strain, although the size of subgrains hardly changes.

Figure 24 shows the variation in the width and length of cells or subgrains and the ratio of length to width with strain for the Type A microstructure. The sizes of cells for the Type B and C microstructures are also marked in Fig. 24. It is found that the width of boundary IIs formed in the early stages of deformation is similar to the size of subgrains at high strains for the Type A microstructure, that is, this value hardly varies with strain. The length of cells or subgrains and the ratio of length to width (l/w) of cells or subgrains decrease markedly with increasing strain. Beyond a strain of 1.5 they reach steady state values.

During cold deformation, grains in polycrystals are subdivided into many crystallites by the formation of dislocation boundaries. Such grain subdivision in rolling and tension has been investigated extensively for f.c.c. metals with medium to high stacking fault energy, such as aluminium, nickel and copper, and a theoretical framework has been established for the evolution of deformation microstructure [1–6]. According to this framework, the grain subdivision takes place on two scales:
1.
on a larger scale into cell blocks bounded by dislocation boundaries such as DDWs and MBs at low to medium strain; and
2.
on a smaller scale into dislocation cells that subdivide the cell blocks and are bounded by ordinary cell boundaries.
At large strains the microstructures evolve into a lamellar structure with boundaries of small to medium misorientation angles mixed with high angle boundaries [30].

The dislocation boundaries which form during hot deformation separate grains into misoriented regions. The grain subdivision process is related to the characteristics of dislocation boundaries. Based on the above microstructural observations, the grain subdivision process depends strongly on grain orientation due to the difference of active slip systems at low strains. Figure 25 shows the process of grain subdivision for three types of microstructure. For the Type A microstructure, the grains are first separated by boundary Is into large regions, and then are separated by boundary IIs [see Fig. 25(a)], or the grains are directly separated by boundary IIs [see Fig. 25(b)]. Afterward, the regions between boundary IIs are subdivided by boundary IIIs into elongated cells, which are converted into approximately square cells with increasing the amount of boundary IIIs. At last the approximately square cells are changed into approximately equiaxed subgrains by the migration of dislocation boundaries. For the Type B microstructure [see Fig. 25(c)], two sets of boundaries are formed along two different directions, leading to elongated cells. Under this circumstance, the elongated cells are separated again by the formation of dislocation boundaries parallel to the short side. The number of boundaries in the elongated cells depends on the ratio of length to width of the elongated cell. If the ratio of length to width is about 2, the elongated cell is separated by a dislocation boundary. If the ratio of length to width is about 3, two dislocation boundaries are formed in the elongated cell and separate this cell into three parts. Finally the square cells are also changed into approximately equiaxed subgrains. For the Type C microstructure [see Fig. 25(d)], the grain subdivision is different from those for the Type A and B microstructures. The Type C microstructure is composed of large cells and cell blocks with many small cells, and the boundaries between cell blocks and large cells have higher misorientation angles than those in cell blocks. This suggests that the grains with the cube orientation are first subdivided by two sets of dislocation boundaries formed on planes near two different slip planes into the large cells more than the subgrains formed at large strains, and then new dislocation boundaries formed in some large cells separate these cells into small cells similar to subgrains, leading to cell blocks. As a result, the dislocation boundaries between cell blocks and large cells have high misorientation angles. The other large cells continue to be separated into subgrains with increasing strain.

The experimental observations show that grain orientation in a polycrystalline has a significant effect on the characteristics of the deformed microstructures. This can be attributed to the effect of the slip pattern on microstructures since the movement of dislocations results in the formation of boundaries. Because the dislocation gliding is related to slip systems with higher Schmid factors, it will be useful to review briefly the expected slip geometry for all grain orientations. Table 5 lists Schmid factors of slip systems for grains observed at strains of 0.14 and 0.53, calculated using a stress state appropriate for plane strain compression (σ 11=−σ 33, σ 22=σ
ij =0).

Since the subgrain boundaries are mainly composed of tilt boundaries, the dislocations in boundaries should come from two different slip planes. In order to form the dislocation boundaries, at least two slip systems from two different slip planes are necessary. Assuming that the slip systems with the highest Schmid factors from two different planes operate, whether the slip systems from the third or fourth slip plane operate depends on the ratio of the highest Schmid factor from the third or fourth slip plane to those from the first and second slip planes. Table 5 gives the values of R 1 and R 2 [R 1=2S 4/(S 1+S 2), R 2=2S 3/(S 1+S 2)], where S 1, S 2, S 3, and S 4 are respectively the highest Schmid factor from four slip planes, and S 1>S 2>S 3>S 4.

For the Type AI microstructure, the values of R 1 and R 2 are <0.7, which suggests the substantial majority of dislocations in boundaries come from two slip planes. The typical grain orientation for the Type AI microstructure is the {011}〈211〉 brass orientation with the R 1 value of 0 and the R 2 value of 0.33. For the Type AII microstructure, the value of R 1 is <0.7, while the value of R 2 is >0.7. Apart from the slip systems from the first and second slip planes, the slip system from the third slip plane also operates. The typical grain orientation for the Type AII microstructure is the {112}〈111〉 copper orientation with the R 1 value of 0 and the R 2 value of 1. For the rotated Goss orientation with the Type B microstructure, eight slip systems a2, a3, b2, b3, c2, c3, d2 and d3 in the Bishop–Hill notation [31] have a Schmid factor of 0.204 and the Schmid factor for the remaining four slip systems is 0. It is obvious that the active slip systems come from four slip planes. By trace analyses, it is found that the angles between the four slip planes and the rolling direction on the longitudinal plane are 0, 90, 0 and 90° for the (011)[0 1 ̄ 1] orientation, respectively. Thus, the dislocation boundaries in grains with a rotated Goss orientation have very high angles to the traces of slip planes since the dislocation boundaries have a macroscopic orientation with an angle between 25 and 55° to RD. For the cube orientation with the Type C microstructure, the slip systems a2, b2, c2, and d2 have the largest Schmid factor of 0.41, and the angles between the slip planes and the rolling direction on the longitudinal plane are 45, −45, −45 and 45° at the (001)[100] orientation, respectively. Although the active slip systems also come from four slip planes for the Type C microstructure, the characteristics of microstructures is different to that for the Type B microstructure due to the difference of Schmid factors and the orientation of slip planes.

ce:section.ce:section-title: Relationship between the type of microstructure and grain orientation
ce:section.ce:para:
In the above section, the variation in Schmid factors with grain orientation in polycrystalline materials plays a significant role in the classification of microstructures. The brass orientation region with the Type AI microstructure and the copper orientation region with the Type AII microstructure can be determined by the values of R 1 and R 2, but the cube orientation region can not be differentiated from the rotated Goss orientation region by the values of R 1 and R 2. Therefore, the other parameters of R 3 and R 4 (R 3=S 3/0.408 and R 4=S 4/0.408) are introduced to describe the slip pattern. For the cube orientation, the values of R 1, R 2, R 3 and R 4 are 1, while for the rotated Goss orientation the values of R 1, R 2, R 3 and R 4 are 1, 1, 0.5 and 0.5, respectively. Because a few grains with the Type B and C microstructures are observed and the microstructures with the Goss and rotated cube orientations are not be observed in the present work, the Euler space can not be divided into regions with different types of microstructure according to the present experimental data. However, the texture formed during deformation is also related to the slip pattern. Based on the characteristics of microstructures and textures the Euler space representing all crystallographic orientations in plane strain compression and rolling can be divided into six regions, as shown in Fig. 26
[32]. The different orientation regions are marked with AI, AII, B, C, D and E. The transmission electron microscopy results on the relationship between the type of microstructure and grain orientation in Fig. 12 are also described in this figure in order to compare with the division of Euler space determined according to the relationship between the slip pattern and grain orientation.

In the AI region, that is, the brass orientation region, the grains have the Type AI microstructure, the boundary IIs are aligned with the slip planes. In the AII region, that is, the copper orientation region, the grains have the Type AII microstructure, the boundary IIs lie on planes far from the slip planes. In the B region, that is, the rotated Goss orientation region, the grains have the Type B microstructure. Two sets of boundaries are formed along two different directions at the same time. The boundaries are also formed on planes far from the slip planes. In contrast to the boundaries in the AII region, the boundaries have higher angles relative to the slip planes. In the C region, that is, the cube orientation region, the grains have the Type C microstructure. The boundaries are formed along two different directions on planes near the slip planes. The spacing between the parallel boundaries is more than the size of subgrain formed at large strains. In the D and E regions, that is, the Goss and rotated cube orientation regions, the grains can be inferred to have similar microstructures based on their slip patterns.

It is noted in Table 5 and Fig. 26 that the type of microstructure in a few grains such as grains 1-15, 1-21, 2-6, and 2-7 does not correspond to the division of Euler space. The reason is that the grain orientation used in the results and discussion is the grain orientation after deformation, not the initial grain orientation.

It is known that the boundaries formed in the early stage of deformation are related to the slip systems determined based on the initial grain orientation. The initial grain orientation rotates towards the stable end orientation during deformation. The grains observed in one orientation region may have started in another orientation region if the initial grain orientation is replaced by the grain orientation after deformation to represent the relationship between the type of microstructure and grain orientation. For example, the grains 1-15, 2-6 and 2-7 with the Type AII microstructure are observed in the AI region, while the grain 1-21 with the microstructure similar to the Type B microstructure moves from the B region to the AI region. On the other hand, the boundary characteristics should be a function of the history, rather than of the immediate orientation. The slip pattern changes when the grain orientation rotates from one region to another region. If the dislocations with different Burgers vectors generated because of the variation in the slip pattern glide to the boundaries, the characteristics of boundaries formed in the early stage of deformation changes. Further studies of the strain dependence of the boundary characteristics are needed to understand the evolution of dislocation boundaries during deformation.

For AA3104 alloy deformed at a temperature of 510°C and a strain rate of 5 s−1 the microstructural evolution has been followed and the structural parameters have been measured. The following conclusions are reached:
•
In the early stages of deformation the microstructural characteristics of individual grains are strongly affected by the grain orientation. In general, the microstructure can be classified into three types according to the grain subdivision and the characteristics of dislocation boundaries. Their characteristics is summarized as follows:
Type A: The grains are separated by a set of dislocation boundaries (boundary II) with a spacing of a few micrometers, and then the regions between boundary IIs are separated by dislocation boundaries (boundary III) into cells. According to the crystallographic preference of boundary II, the structures (Type A) can be classified into two types, one (Type AI) with boundary II which are on {111} planes, the other (Type AII) with boundary II which are not on {111} planes. For the Type A microstructure, some grains also undergo a macroscopic subdivision on a grain size scale before the formation of boundary II.
Type B: The grains are directly separated by two sets of dislocation boundaries into cells. There are high angles between the trace of boundaries and the nearest {111} trace.
Type C: The microstructures are composed of large cells and cell blocks with many small cells. The boundaries between cell blocks and large cells have higher misorientation angles than those in cell blocks. Compared with Type A, the cell block boundaries have very high misorientation angles.
•
For the Type A microstructure, the average misorientation angle across dislocation boundaries decreases in the sequence of boundary Is, boundary IIs and boundary IIIs at a given strain and grain orientation. The misorientation angle across boundary IIs for the Type AI microstructure is lower than for the Type AII microstructure. The misorientation angle across all boundaries increases with increasing strain. For the Type C microstructure, the misorientation angle across the boundaries between cell blocks and large cells is larger than that in cell blocks.
•
With increasing strain, the width of cells or subgrains hardly changes, while the length of cells or subgrains and the ratio of length to width of subgrains decrease.
•
The Euler space representing all crystallographic orientations in plane strain compression is divided into different regions to represent the relationship between microstructures and grain orientation. It is found that the microstructures in grains near the brass orientation correspond to the Type AI microstructure. The grains near the copper orientation appear as the Type AII microstructure. The Type B microstructure is found in the region near the rotated Goss orientation. The Type C microstructure is concentrated in the cube orientation.
